<div class="default-page">
  <div class="header">
    <h1 id="main-title" class="container"><%= __('Cars REST API') %></h1>
    <h3 class="container">This is a sample SailsJS REST API which also uses MongoDB and ElasticSearch.  By <a href="https://twitter.com/SharePointOscar">@SharePointOscar</a>.</h3>
    
  </div>
  <div class="main container clearfix">
    <h1>Getting started</h1>
    <p>This app already contains a Helm Chart with dependencies.  If you are using Jenkins X, you can simply import it.  For more details on features and configuration, please look at the README.md</p>
    <ul class="getting-started">
      <li class="clearfix">
        <div class="step">
          <div class="sprite one"></div>
          <h3>Access the Cars REST API Swagger Documentation </h3>
          <p>
            If you are seeing this page, that means you've successfully deployed the app, so congratulations!  To access the API Docs, you will go to the URL where it is deployed, example <code>http://myapi/docs</code>.  In the textbox, you will want to enter that same url and click Explore. You will see the Swagger API documentation and can actually test endpoints!
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="clearfix">
        <div class="step">
          <div class="sprite two"></div>
          <h3>
            Access Cars API Using Postman
          </h3>
          <p>
            Simply paste the endpoint URL in the Postman client, and select the METHOD.  For example, to get all Cars use <code>cars-rest-api.jx-staging.34.82.12.120.nip.io/car</code>. Change url based on where the API is deployed.  
          </p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li class="clearfix">
        <div class="step">
          <div class="sprite three"></div>
          <h3>
            Explore the Helm Charts
          </h3>
          <p>Feel free to explore the Helm Charts and see how dependencies are declared, along with their initial configuration.</p>

        </div>
      </li>
    </ul>
